[[Image:Halo 1 2 and 3 covers.jpg|thumb|right|The covers of ''Halo: Combat Evolved'', the ''Halo 2'' Limited Edition and the ''Halo 3'' Legendary Edition]]
This is a '''list of media''' related to the [[Halo (series)|'''''Halo'' series''']]. Central to the ''Halo'' series are the three [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]]s ''[[Halo: Combat Evolved]]'', ''[[Halo 2]]'' and ''[[Halo 3]]'', with [[novel]]s, [[soundtrack]]s, and other media also available. The story of the series is about the [[Master Chief (Halo)|Master Chief]], a [[cybernetics|cybernetically]] enhanced human super-soldier and his [[artificial intelligence]] (AI) companion, [[Cortana]], as the humans of a futuristic universe battle the [[Covenant (Halo)|Covenant]], a theocratic alliance of alien races. The ''Halo'' series has been used as the basis for [[machinima]] production such as ''[[Red vs. Blue]]'' and [[fan fiction]], however this list covers only media produced or endorsed by the creator, [[Bungie Studios]]. 

The ''Halo'' video games have been highly successful and influential; the first game was labeled the [[killer application]] of [[Microsoft|Microsoft's]] [[Xbox]] and was credited with selling many consoles.<ref name=egmreview>{{Citation| periodical= [[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]| publisher= [[Ziff Davis]]| issue = 150| pages = 224}}</ref><ref name=theage>{{cite web| last=Hill| first=Jason| date=2004-11-04| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Livewire/Xbox-wears-a-Halo-of-success/2004/11/03/1099362207594.html| title=Xbox wears a Halo of success| work=[[The Age]]| accessdate=2006-09-19}}</ref> ''Halo: Combat Evolved'' is also noted for its intuitive control scheme that has been used by many console first person shooters since.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://au.top100.ign.com/2007/ign_top_game_32.html| title=32. Halo: Combat Evolved| publisher=[[IGN]]| accessdate=2007-12-08| quote=... a tight, intuitive control scheme that finally made first-person shooters make sense on a console.}}</ref> ''Halo 2'' sold 2.4&nbsp;million copies making [[US$]]125 million in the first 24&nbsp;hours after its release beating the record for highest grossing entertainment release,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/2004/11/10/news_6112915.html| title=Microsoft raises estimated first-day Halo 2 sales to $125 million-plus| publisher=[[GameSpot]]| accessdate=2006-03-15| last = Thorsen| first = Tor| date=2004-11-10}}</ref> release however ''Halo 3'' grossed US$170&nbsp;million on its first day, $45&nbsp;million more.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamepro.com/news.cfm?article_id=136548| title=Analyst: Halo 3 shatters retail record; sells $170M in 24 hrs| accessdate=2007-09-26| author= Snow, Blake| publisher= [[GamePro]]}}</ref> ''Halo 2'' and ''Halo 3'' are also the best selling titles of their respective consoles, the [[Xbox]] and the [[Xbox 360]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117976843.html?categoryid=2525&cs=1| title=Videogame sequels hit geek peak| first=Ben| last=Fritz| date=2007-11-30| publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| accessdate=2007-12-03}}</ref><ref name="gow">{{cite web| first=Asher| last=Moses| url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/biztech/prepare-for-allout-war/2007/08/30/1188067256196.html?page=fullpage| date=2007-08-30| title=Prepare for all-out war| work=The Sydney Morning Herald| publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]| accessdate=2007-11-05}}</ref>

